                <h2>Scenario: $100K Discrepancy Found at Month-End Close</h2>
<p>On the night of November 30th, Xiao Lin from an overseas tool app's performance marketing team received a message from the finance department right after uploading the last batch of ad creatives:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"Recharge amount: $82,000 USD. Platform reported spend: $79,500 USD. Invoice amount: $81,200 USD. None of these figures match. Which one is correct?"</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is not an isolated case. Reconciliation for overseas ad accounts is far more complex than domestic platforms. Currency mismatches between recharges and spending, billing cycle gaps versus invoice issuance dates, and exchange rate conversions across multiple accounts make financial discrepancies a monthly headache for nearly every overseas team.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Problem Breakdown: Where Reconciliation Gaps Usually Occur</h2>
<h3>Recharge Amount ≠ Actual Credited Amount</h3>
<p>Many teams assume the full recharge amount reaches their account, but platforms typically deduct a service fee of 2%–5%. Common causes include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Platform service fee deducted at recharge (2%–5%)</li>
<li>Rebate delays from代理商 (agency) channels</li>
<li>Exchange rate fluctuations affecting actual credited amounts</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to identify</strong>: Compare the actual deduction on the payment receipt against the account balance change shown on the platform.</p>
<h3>Platform Spend ≠ Invoice Amount</h3>
<p>Ad platforms bill based on actual spend, but invoices are issued according to the billing cycle—daily, weekly, or monthly. Common reasons for misalignment:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Timezone differences</strong>: Platform reports in UTC, finance reconciles in local time</li>
<li><strong>Refund deductions</strong>: Negative spend from refunds not yet reflected in billing</li>
<li><strong>Grant credits</strong>: Platform bonus credits counted in spend but excluded from invoices</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to identify</strong>: Download daily spend reports from the platform backend and manually sum them up to compare against the monthly invoice.</p>
<h3>Account Balance ≠ Available Spending Limit</h3>
<p>For teams managing multiple ad accounts, recharge funds flow between parent and sub-accounts. If finance only records parent account transactions, sub-account spending cannot be matched to the corresponding recharge records.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Action Steps: Xiao Lin's 4-Step Reconciliation SOP</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Pull Three Data Tables</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Data Source</th>
<th>Key Fields</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Recharge Records</td>
<td>Date, channel, actual debit, amount in original currency</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Platform Spend Reports</td>
<td>Date, Account ID, spend amount, currency</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Invoice Archive</td>
<td>Invoice number, issue date, tax-inclusive amount, platform name</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Step 2: Standardize the Conversion Base</h3>
<p>Convert all amounts to the same currency and timezone. It is recommended to use the <strong>spend currency shown on the platform</strong> as the base and convert recharge and invoice amounts using the daily mid-market rate.</p>
<h3>Step 3: Trace Discrepancies Level by Level</h3>
<pre><code>Total Recharge $82,000 USD
− Platform Service Fee (~3%)  −$2,460 USD
= Actual Credited $79,540 USD ≈ Platform Spend $79,500 USD ✓

Platform Spend $79,500 USD
+ Estimated Refund Deductions −$1,300 USD (not included in invoice)
= Invoice Amount $81,200 USD ✓
</code></pre>
<h3>Step 4: Document Supporting Evidence</h3>
<p>For the minor $40 discrepancy caused by timezone conversion, retain platform spend screenshots and recharge records as supporting documentation. Process it as a small variance write-off in the next reconciliation cycle.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Result: Discrepancies Categorized and Resolved</h2>
<p>Through this 4-step process, Xiao Lin confirmed:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>3% service fee</strong> was the main cause of recharge vs. credited amount gap — a normal platform charge</li>
<li><strong>Refund deductions not yet processed</strong> created a $1,700 gap between spend and invoice — needed to contact platform support for a credit memo</li>
<li><strong>$40 timezone conversion variance</strong> was within acceptable tolerance, documented for archiving</li>
</ul>
<p>At the next month's reconciliation, the team added two new columns to the recharge log — "Actual Credited Amount" and "Service Fee Deduction" — and the three statements finally aligned.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Key Takeaways: 3 Habits to Avoid Reconciliation Headaches</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Record "actual debit amount" at recharge time, not the nominal recharge value</strong></li>
<li><strong>Cross-check invoices against platform spend reports immediately upon receipt — do not wait until month-end</strong></li>
<li><strong>Teams with multiple accounts should use a unified consolidation sheet with individual sub-account spend ledgers</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>There are no shortcuts to overseas ad financial management, but establishing standardized recording practices and a consistent reconciliation process can transform month-end close from "working until midnight" to "done in 30 minutes."</p>
